Get number of factors using parallel analysis

res = get_factor_num(
    df=df,
    value_cols=q_cols,
    figs_path=NULL)

## Parallel analysis suggests that the number of factors =  5  and the number of components =  NA
# R returns: Number of factors = with eigen values > eigen values of random data
factor_num = res[["factor_num"]]
factor_num
## [1] 5

Fit the EFA with those number of factors and remove items

res = fit_fa_model(
    df=df,
    factor_num=factor_num,
    rotate=rotate,
    value_cols=q_cols,
    loading_thresh=loading_thresh)

df_filtered = res[["df_filtered"]]

Get a better clusters plot

using hierarchical clustering and mclust package in R

check to make sure clusters are the same with psych package if you care

res = explore_vars_cor_dt(
    df=df,
    value_cols=accepted_items,
    cluster_num=factor_num,
    figs_path=figs_path,
    fn_suffix=paste0("hosseini_", filter),
    latex_fn=NULL)
## [1] "data.frame"
cluster_df = res[["cluster_res" ]][["cluster_df"]]
obtained_clusters = cluster_df[["cluster"]]
res[["cluster_plt_func"]]()
